<div class="bauhaus-landing">
      <section class="hero bauhaus-hero">
        <div class="hero-left">
          <h1 class="hero-title">NeoBrutalism</h1>
          <div class="hero-ctas">
            <a class="btn large" href="/work.html">Explore Works</a>
            <a class="btn outline" href="/learn.html">Read &amp; Learn</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-right">
          <p class="hero-desc">Neo-brutalism in web design is a bold, raw visual style that intentionally rejects polished, ultra-refined interfaces in favor of an unfiltered, almost “unfinished” aesthetic. It draws inspiration from traditional brutalist architecture—focusing on honesty, functionality, and visible structure—by using thick borders, harsh edges, high-contrast colors, oversized typography, and simple, flat elements. Instead of subtle gradients, soft shadows, or rounded corners, neo-brutalist design leans into blunt shapes, asymmetry, and layouts that feel more like wireframes or experimental posters. The result is a visually striking, anti-corporate look that emphasizes clarity, personality, and a refreshingly direct user experience.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="featured">
        <h2 class="section-title">Featured</h2>
        <div class="featured-grid">
          {% set _count = 0 %}
          {% for p in projects %}
            {% if p.featured and _count < 3 %}
              <a class="feature {% if p.highlight == 'purple' %}purple{% endif %}" href="/{{ p.url }}">
                <img src="/{{ p.image }}" alt="{{ p.title }}" loading="lazy" />
                <div class="meta"><strong>{{ p.title }}</strong><span>{{ p.year }}</span></div>
              </a>
              {% set _count = _count + 1 %}
            {% endif %}
          {% endfor %}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="notes">
        <h3 class="section-title">Core Principles of Neo‑Brutalism</h3>
        <div class="notes-grid">
          <article class="card">
            <h4>Material Honesty</h4>
            <p>Expose materials and finishes — concrete, raw metals, and paper — without decorative masking.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h4>Monumentality & Scale</h4>
            <p>Favor bold, large-scale forms and generous negative space to emphasize presence and mass.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h4>Structural Expression</h4>
            <p>Reveal structure and joinery as compositional elements rather than hiding them behind ornament.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h4>Typographic Rigour</h4>
            <p>Use strict grids, large type, and high-contrast typography to communicate hierarchy directly.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h4>Raw Texture & Contrast</h4>
            <p>Pair smooth planes with coarse textures; embrace visible tooling, seams, and edges.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h4>Functional Clarity</h4>
            <p>Let function drive form: clear systems, plain interfaces, and unapologetic utility.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="contact-teaser">
        <h3 class="section-title">Have a project or question?</h3>
